# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: fred-mann-baseball
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:fred-mann-baseball/1882-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1882 throughout the world.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/1887-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1887 throughout the world.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/baseball-reference] Founder Sean Forman began developing the website while working on his Ph.D. dissertation in applied math and computational science at the University of Iowa.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/baseball-reference] While writing his dissertation, he had also been writing articles on and blogging about sabermetrics.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/baseball-reference] Forman's database was originally built from the *Total Baseball* series of baseball encyclopedias.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/baseball-reference] The website went online in April 2000, after first being launched in February 2000 as part of the website for the *Big Bad Baseball Annual*.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/baseball-reference] It was originally built as a web interface to the Lahman Baseball Database, though it now employs a variety of data sources.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/baseball-reference] In 2004, Forman founded Sports Reference.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/baseball-reference] Sports Reference is a website that came out of the Baseball Reference website.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/baseball-reference] The company was incorporated as Sports Reference, LLC in 2007.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/baseball-reference] In 2006, Forman left his job as a math professor at Saint Joseph's University to focus on Baseball Reference full-time.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/baseball-reference] In February 2009, Fantasy Sports Ventures took a minority stake in Sports Reference, for a "low seven-figure sum".
[src:fred-mann-baseball/baseball-reference] In late April 2021, the site changed a number of identifying names, "discontinuing the use of nicknames that are racially or ethnically influenced" and "names based upon a player's disability", such as Chief Bender and Dummy Hoy, who are now listed as Charles Bender and Billy Hoy, respectively.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/baseball-reference] To compare ballplayers to one-another it offers "Black Ink" and "Gray Ink" tests, which tally a player's dominance and overall productivity against his peers.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/baseball-reference] In 2012, it began to offer Jay Jaffe's Jaffe Wins Above Replacement Score (JAWS) statistic for comparing players of different eras against each other by weighing their performance in the prime as well as their entire career.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/baseball-reference] Baseball Reference began including its version of Wins Above Replacement (WAR) in 2010.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/baseball-reference] Its version determining a player's value differs slightly from other baseball statistics websites, including FanGraphs and Baseball Prospectus.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/baseball-reference] Baseball Reference has its own baseball encyclopedia, a wiki called "Baseball Reference Bullpen", which can be edited by anyone and is modeled after Wikipedia.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/baseball-reference] As of November 2025, the Bullpen contains more than 123,000 articles.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/batting-average-baseball] In baseball, **batting average** (**BA**) is determined by dividing a player's hits by their total at-bats.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/batting-average-baseball] It is usually rounded to three decimal places and read without the decimal: A player with a batting average of .300 is said to be "batting three hundred".
[src:fred-mann-baseball/batting-average-baseball] If necessary to break ties, batting averages could be taken beyond the .001 measurement.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/batting-average-baseball] In this context, .001 is considered a "point", such that a .235 batter is five points higher than a .230 batter.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/batting-average-baseball] Henry Chadwick, an English statistician raised on cricket, was an influential figure in the early history of baseball.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/batting-average-baseball] He is credited with creating the modern box score, in 1859, and the practice of denoting a strikeout with a "K".
[src:fred-mann-baseball/batting-average-baseball] In 1869, another early baseball proponent, Alfred Wright, published an end-of-season summary that included the average number of times a batter had "clean" hits on a *per game* basis.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/batting-average-baseball] In 1871, a writer for the *New York Clipper*, Hervie Dobson, proposed that a batter's "average is found by dividing his total 'times first base on clean hits' by his total number of times he went to the bat"—hits divided by at bats.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/batting-average-baseball] By 1874, some teams were calculating batting averages, and by 1876, it was being calculated by all teams of the National League.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/batting-average-baseball] In modern times, a season batting average of .300 or higher is considered to be excellent, and an average higher than .400 is a nearly unachievable goal.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/batting-average-baseball] The last Major League Baseball (MLB) player to do so, with enough plate appearances to qualify for the batting championship, was Ted Williams of the Boston Red Sox, who hit .406 in 1941.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/batting-average-baseball] Note that batting averages are rounded; entering the final day of the 1941 season, Williams was at 179-for-448, which is .39955 and would have been recorded as .400 via rounding.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/batting-average-baseball] However, Williams played in both games of a doubleheader, went 6-for-8, and ended the season 185-for-456, which is .40570 and becomes .406 when rounded.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/batting-average-baseball] Since 1941, no American League or National League player has hit .400 or above—the highest single-season average in those leagues has been .394 by Tony Gwynn of the San Diego Padres in 1994.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/batting-average-baseball] Wade Boggs hit .401 over a 162-game span with Boston from June 9, 1985, to June 6, 1986, but never hit above .368 for an MLB season.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/batting-average-baseball] There have been numerous attempts to explain the disappearance of the .400 hitter, with one of the more rigorous discussions of this question appearing in Stephen Jay Gould's 1996 book *Full House*.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/batting-average-baseball] Josh Gibson hit .466 in 1943 while playing for the Homestead Grays of the Negro National League, one of several leagues within Negro league baseball that are now recognized by MLB.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/batting-average-baseball] Gibson holds the record for highest major-league career batting average at .371, four points higher than Ty Cobb, who has the second-highest career average at .367.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/batting-average-baseball] The record for lowest career batting average for a player with more than 2,500 at-bats belongs to Bill Bergen, a catcher who played from 1901 to 1911 and recorded a .170 average in 3,028 career at-bats.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/batting-average-baseball] Hugh Duffy, who played from 1888 to 1906, is credited with the highest single-season batting average, having hit .440 in 1894.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/batting-average-baseball] The modern-era (post-1900) record for highest batting average for a season is held by Nap Lajoie, who hit .426 in 1901, the first year of play for the American League.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/batting-average-baseball] The modern-era record for the lowest batting average for a player that qualified for the batting title is held by Chris Davis, who hit .168 in 2018.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/batting-average-baseball] While finishing six plate appearances short of qualifying for the batting title, Adam Dunn of the Chicago White Sox hit .159 for the 2011 season, nine points lower than the record.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/batting-average-baseball] The highest batting average for a rookie was .408 in 1911 by Shoeless Joe Jackson.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/batting-average-baseball] The league batting average in MLB for the 2018 season was .248, with the highest modern-era MLB average being .296 in 1930, and the lowest being .237 in 1968.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/batting-average-baseball] For non-pitchers, a batting average below .230 is often considered poor, and one below .200 is usually unacceptable.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/batting-average-baseball] This latter level is sometimes referred to as "The Mendoza Line", named for Mario Mendoza—a lifetime .215 hitter but a good defensive shortstop.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/batting-average-baseball] Sabermetrics, the study of baseball statistics, considers batting average a weak measure of performance because it does not correlate as well as other measures to runs scored, thereby causing it to have little predictive value.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/batting-average-baseball] Batting average does not take into account bases on balls (walks) or power, whereas other statistics such as on-base percentage and slugging percentage have been specifically designed to measure such concepts.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/batting-average-baseball] Adding these statistics together form a player's on-base plus slugging or "OPS".
[src:fred-mann-baseball/batting-average-baseball] This is commonly seen as a much better, though not perfect, indicator of a player's overall batting ability as it is a measure of hitting for average, hitting for power, and drawing walks.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/batting-average-baseball] In 1887, bases on balls (walks) were counted as hits by the major leagues in existence at the time.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/batting-average-baseball] This inflated batting averages, with 11 players batting .400 or better, and the experiment was abandoned the following season.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/batting-average-baseball] In rare instances, players have concluded their careers with a perfect batting average of 1.000—through the 2021 season, there were 94 such players in major-league history, 83 of whom recorded exactly one hit in one at bat.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/batting-average-baseball] Only one player with a 1.000 average has had three hits—outfielder John Paciorek (1963), who had three hits in three at bats; he also had two walks, and scored four runs.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/batting-average-baseball] Players who had two hits in their only two at bats include: pitcher Frank O'Connor (1893), catcher Mike Hopkins (1902), pitcher Doc Tonkin (1907), pitcher Hal Deviney (1920), pitcher Fred Schemanske (1923), pitcher Chet Kehn (1942), second baseman Steve Biras (1944), and pitcher Jason Roach (2003).
[src:fred-mann-baseball/batting-average-baseball] Pitcher Esteban Yan, who played in 472 major-league games from 1996 to 2006, mainly in the American League (where pitchers have rarely batted since the introduction of the designated hitter in 1973), also had two hits in his only two at bats, one a home run.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/batting-average-baseball] The MLB batting averages championships (often referred to as "the batting title") are awarded annually to the player in each league with the highest batting average.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/batting-average-baseball] Ty Cobb holds the MLB and American League (AL) record for most batting titles, officially winning 11 in his career.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/batting-average-baseball] The National League (NL) record of eight batting titles is shared by Honus Wagner and Tony Gwynn.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/batting-average-baseball] This is officially Rule 10.22(a), but it is also known as the "Tony Gwynn rule" because the Padres' player won the batting crown in 1996 with a .353 average on just 498 plate appearances (i.e., he was four short).
[src:fred-mann-baseball/batting-average-baseball] Gwynn was awarded the title since he would have led the league even if he had gone 0-for-4 in those missing plate appearances.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/batting-average-baseball] His average would have dropped to .349, five points better than second-place Ellis Burks' .344.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/batting-average-baseball] In 2012, a one-time amendment to the rule was made to disqualify Melky Cabrera from the title.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/batting-average-baseball] Cabrera requested that he be disqualified after serving a suspension that season for a positive testosterone test.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/batting-average-baseball] He had batted .346 with 501 plate appearances, and the original rule would have awarded him the title over San Francisco Giants teammate Buster Posey, who won batting .336.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/batting-average-baseball] The highest recorded single-season batting average in Minor League Baseball is .462, accomplished by Gary Redus in 1978, when he played for the Billings Mustangs, an affiliate of the Cincinnati Reds in the Rookie Advanced-level Pioneer League.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/batting-average-baseball] Redus was 117-for-253 in 68 games, as the Pioneer League only plays from June to early September.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/batting-average-baseball] Redus went on to play in MLB from 1982 through 1994, batting .252 during his MLB career.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/batting-average-baseball] In Nippon Professional Baseball (NPB), the leader in career batting average is Isao Harimoto, a member of the Japanese Baseball Hall of Fame, who hit .319 in his NPB career.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/batting-average-baseball] Ichiro Suzuki batted .353 in NPB, but does not have enough NPB career at-bats to qualify for the league's title.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/batting-average-baseball] Sadaharu Oh had a batting average of .355 in 1973 season.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/batting-average-baseball] Randy Bass had a batting average of .389 in 1986 season.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/batting-average-baseball] In KBO League (KBO), the leader in career batting average is Jung-hoo Lee, who hit .340 in his KBO career and is currently an active player.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/batting-average-baseball] Baek In-chun had a batting average of .412 in 1982 season.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/batting-average-baseball] This is the highest batting average of one season in KBO League.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/center-fielder] A **center fielder**, abbreviated **CF**, is the outfielder in baseball who plays defense in **center field** – the baseball and softball fielding position between left field and right field.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/center-fielder] In the numbering system used to record defensive plays, the center fielder is assigned the number 8.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/center-fielder] Outfielders must cover large distances, so speed, instincts and quickness to react to the ball are key.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/center-fielder] They must be able to catch fly balls above their heads and on the run.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/center-fielder] They must be able to throw the ball accurately over a long distance to be effective.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/center-fielder] As well as the requirements above, the center fielder must be the outfielder who has the best combination of speed and throwing distance.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/center-fielder] The center fielder "covers more 'grass' than any other player" (see photo) and, most likely, will catch the most fly balls.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/center-fielder] The position also has the greatest responsibility among the three outfielders for coordinating their play to prevent collisions when converging on a fly ball, and on plays where the center fielder does not make the catch, he must position himself behind the corner outfielder as backup.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/center-fielder] The center outfielder is the captain of the outfield and has the authority to call off the corner fielders when he has a better chance to catch the ball.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/center-fielder] Aside from requiring more speed and range, the center field position is slightly easier to field because balls tend to fly on a straight path, rather than curving as they do for the other outfield positions.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/center-fielder] A center fielder's vision and depth perception is a coveted skill and must be above average.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/center-fielder] Because the position requires a good arm and fast legs, center field is generally where the team puts its best all-around athletes; as a result, center fielders are often fine hitters as well.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/center-fielder] Many center fielders are renowned as excellent batters and base runners.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/center-fielder] When a base runner is trying to steal second base the center fielder must back up second base on throws from the catcher to second base in case the second baseman misses the catch or it is a bad throw.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/cleveland-blues-aa] The **Cleveland Spiders** were an American professional baseball team based in Cleveland, Ohio.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/cleveland-blues-aa] The team competed at the major league level from 1887 to 1899, first for two seasons as a member of the now-defunct American Association (AA), followed by eleven seasons in the National League (NL).
[src:fred-mann-baseball/cleveland-blues-aa] Early names for the team included the **Forest Citys** and **Blues**.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/cleveland-blues-aa] The name Spiders itself emerged early in the team's inaugural NL season of 1889, owing to new black-and-gray uniforms and the skinny, long-limbed look of many players (thereby resembling the spider).
[src:fred-mann-baseball/cleveland-blues-aa] National League Park served as the team's home for its first four seasons until the opening of League Park in 1891.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/cleveland-blues-aa] Amid seven straight winning seasons under manager Patsy Tebeau, the team finished second in the National League three times – in 1892, 1895, and 1896.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/cleveland-blues-aa] While the Spiders never won the National League pennant, the club did win the 1895 Temple Cup, a two-team league championship playoff predating the World Series.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/cleveland-blues-aa] The Spiders beat that year's pennant winner, the Baltimore Orioles (unrelated to the modern franchise), four games to one in a best-of-seven game series.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/cleveland-blues-aa] Six Spiders players were later inducted into the National Baseball Hall of Fame, including left fielder Jesse Burkett and pitcher Cy Young.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/cleveland-blues-aa] In 1899, owners Frank and Stanley Robison purchased a second team – the bankrupt St.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/cleveland-blues-aa] Louis NL franchise – and sent all of the Spiders' top talent to that club, including future Hall-of-Famers Young, Burkett, and Bobby Wallace.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/cleveland-blues-aa] The resulting Spiders roster finished the 1899 season 20–134, a record which remains the worst for a single season in major league history.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/cleveland-blues-aa] The Spiders were subsequently one of four teams contracted by the National League that year.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/cleveland-blues-aa] Partly in response to the Robison brothers' actions – which effectively ended the Spiders franchise – the practice of "syndicate ownership" was later banned.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/cleveland-blues-aa] Spiders outfielder Louis Sockalexis played for the team during its final three seasons and is often credited as the first Native American to play major league baseball.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/cleveland-blues-aa] The Cleveland Guardians, major league successor to the Spiders in Cleveland, have long cited Sockalexis as the inspiration for their controversial former team name – "Indians" – though that claim is disputed.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/cleveland-blues-aa] The Spiders were the third professional baseball franchise based in Cleveland.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/cleveland-blues-aa] The first team, Forest City, which played from 1870 through 1872, was initially an independent team before joining the National Association of Professional Base Ball Players for two seasons before disbanding.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/cleveland-blues-aa] They were followed in 1879 by the city's first National League team, the Cleveland Blues, which folded after the 1884 season.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/cleveland-blues-aa] After the 1886 season, the Pittsburgh Alleghenys left the American Association (AA) to join the National League.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/cleveland-blues-aa] The AA, then considered a major league, chose the Cleveland group headed by Frank Robison as an expansion team to begin play in 1887 over proposals from Kansas City and Detroit.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/cleveland-blues-aa] Later, Robison's brother Stanley was added to the ownership group.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/cleveland-blues-aa] Initially, the team was known as the Forest Citys, drawing on the city's nickname and the nickname that had been used on the city's two previous professional baseball teams.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/cleveland-blues-aa] The nickname Blues was also used again in reference to the team uniforms.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/cleveland-blues-aa] The Forest Citys were a weak team in their early years.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/cleveland-blues-aa] In 1889, they moved to the National League and became known as the Spiders, reportedly after comments from a team executive assessing the players.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/cleveland-blues-aa] Brunell, this team executive who also doubled as sportswriter for *The Plain Dealer*, noted the combination of the team's new black-and-gray uniforms together with the sight of several skinny, long-limbed players.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/cleveland-blues-aa] He joked the team should be called "Spiders", and the name stuck.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/cleveland-blues-aa] The team started to improve in 1891, largely due to the signing of future Baseball Hall of Fame pitcher Cy Young.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/cleveland-blues-aa] The Spiders had their first taste of success in 1892 when they finished 93–56 overall; winning the second half by three games over Boston with a 53–23 record.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/cleveland-blues-aa] Other than standout second baseman Cupid Childs, the Spiders had an unremarkable offense.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/cleveland-blues-aa] Their success in 1892 was built on pitching strength; Cy Young was the NL's most dominant hurler, and 22-year-old George Cuppy had an outstanding rookie year.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/cleveland-blues-aa] Following the season, a "World's Championship Series" exhibition was played between Cleveland and the first-half winner Boston Beaneaters, but the Spiders could only muster one tie in six games.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/cleveland-blues-aa] In 1895, the Spiders again finished second, this time to the equally rough-and-tumble Baltimore Orioles.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/cleveland-blues-aa] Young again led the league in wins, and speedy left fielder Jesse Burkett won the batting title with a .409 average.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/cleveland-blues-aa] The Spiders won the Temple Cup, an 1890s postseason series between the first- and second-place teams in the NL.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/cleveland-blues-aa] Amid fan rowdyism and garbage-throwing, the Spiders won four of five games against Baltimore, including two wins for Cy Young.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/cleveland-blues-aa] The 1895 championship was the high-water mark for the franchise.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/cleveland-blues-aa] The following season, Baltimore and Cleveland again finished first and second in the NL, but in the battle for the 1896 Temple Cup, the second-place Spiders were swept in four games.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/cleveland-blues-aa] In 1897, despite a winning record, the franchise finished fifth, a season highlighted by Young throwing the first of three career no-hitters on September 18.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/cleveland-blues-aa] The Spiders again finished fifth in 1898.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/cleveland-blues-aa] In 1899, the Spiders' owners, the Robison brothers, bought the St.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/cleveland-blues-aa] Louis Browns out of bankruptcy and changed their name to the Perfectos.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/cleveland-blues-aa] However, they kept the Spiders as well—a blatant conflict of interest.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/cleveland-blues-aa] Believing the Perfectos would draw greater attendance in more densely populated St.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/cleveland-blues-aa] Louis, the Robisons transferred most of the Cleveland stars, including future Baseball Hall of Famers Cy Young, Jesse Burkett, and Bobby Wallace, to St.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/cleveland-blues-aa] They also shifted a large number of Cleveland home games to the road (for instance, the original Opening Day game was shifted to St.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/cleveland-blues-aa] With a decimated roster, the Spiders made a wretched showing.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/cleveland-blues-aa] They finished with a dismal win-loss record of 20–134 (.130), the worst in MLB history, 84 games behind the pennant-winning Brooklyn Superbas and 35 games behind the next-to-last (11th) place Washington Senators.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/cleveland-blues-aa] Their batting records were the worst in the league in runs, hits, doubles, triples, home runs, walks, stolen bases, on-base percentage, and slugging percentage.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/cleveland-blues-aa] The Robisons announced after buying the Perfectos that they intended to run the Spiders as a "sideshow", and Cleveland fans apparently took them at their word.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/cleveland-blues-aa] The Spiders' first 16 home games drew a total of 3,179 fans, or an average of 199 fans per game.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/cleveland-blues-aa] Due to these meager attendance figures, the other 11 NL teams refused to come to League Park, as their cut of the revenue from ticket sales did not even begin to cover their hotel and travel expenses.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/cleveland-blues-aa] The Spiders were thus forced to play 85 of their remaining 93 games on the road.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/cleveland-blues-aa] Counting the large number of home games that had been shifted to the road earlier in the season, they only played 42 home games during the season, including only eight after July 1, and finished 9–33 (.214) at home and 11–101 (.098) on the road.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/cleveland-blues-aa] Only 6,088 fans paid to attend Spiders home games in 1899, for a pitiful average of a mere 145 spectators per game in 9,000-seat League Park.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/cleveland-blues-aa] The 101 road losses is a major-league record that will never be threatened, as current scheduling practices have teams play a maximum of 81 away games.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/cleveland-blues-aa] The team's longest winning streak of the season was two games, which they accomplished once: on May 20–21.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/cleveland-blues-aa] Spiders opponents scored ten or more runs 49 times in 154 games.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/cleveland-blues-aa] Pitchers Jim Hughey (4–30) and Charlie Knepper (4–22) tied for the team lead in wins.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/cleveland-blues-aa] The 1962 New York Mets, 40–120 (.250), and the 2024 Chicago White Sox, 41–121 (.253), own the modern records in their respective leagues for the most losses, and thus draw frequent comparisons to the 1899 Spiders for futility.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/cleveland-blues-aa] The Robisons' decision to effectively reduce the Spiders to minor league status, along with other intra-league raiding such as that conducted by the Dodgers and to a lesser extent the Pittsburgh Pirates, unwittingly helped pave the way to the National League's loss of its major league monopoly.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/cleveland-blues-aa] The 12th-place Spiders were one of four teams contracted out of the National League at the end of the 1899 season (the others were the 11th-place Senators, the ninth-place Louisville Colonels and the bankrupt fourth-place Baltimore Orioles).
[src:fred-mann-baseball/cleveland-blues-aa] The 1899 fiasco played a role in the major leagues passing a rule which barred one person from owning controlling interest in two clubs.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/cleveland-blues-aa] The Robisons sold the assets of the Spiders team to Charles Somers and John Kilfoyle in 1900.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/cleveland-blues-aa] In 1900, the then-minor American League (previously the Western League) moved the Grand Rapids (baseball) team in to take the Spiders' place, and called the Cleveland Lake Shores.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/cleveland-blues-aa] In 1901, after the American League declared major league status, the team was called the Cleveland Blues, eventually the Cleveland Indians, and now the Cleveland Guardians.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/cleveland-blues-aa] The Cleveland Guardians have long claimed Spiders outfielder Louis Sockalexis as the inspiration for their controversial former team name – "Indians" – in use from 1915 to 2021.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/cleveland-blues-aa] Sockalexis played three seasons for the Cleveland Spiders, from 1897 to 1899, and is often credited as the first Native American to play professional baseball at the major league level.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/cleveland-blues-aa] During his time with the Spiders, the press often referred to the team as the Indians or "Tebeau's Indians".
[src:fred-mann-baseball/cleveland-blues-aa] The Cleveland Guardians claim has been disputed, however, including in a 2012 *Cleveland Scene* essay titled "The Curse of Chief Wahoo", which argues the organization cited Sockalexis in part to justify use of the "Indians" name.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/columbus-buckeyes-aa] The **Columbus Buckeyes** were a professional baseball team in the American Association from 1883 to 1884.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/columbus-buckeyes-aa] In two seasons they won 101 games and lost 104 for a winning percentage of .493.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/columbus-buckeyes-aa] Their home games were played at Recreation Park in Columbus, Ohio.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/columbus-buckeyes-aa] The Buckeyes were managed by Horace Phillips in 1883 (32–65) and Gus Schmelz in 1884 (69–39).
[src:fred-mann-baseball/columbus-buckeyes-aa] Some of their top players were pitchers Ed "Cannonball" Morris, Frank Mountain, and Ed Dundon, the first deaf player in the major leagues, and outfielder Tom Brown.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/columbus-buckeyes-aa] In 1884, the Buckeyes threw two no-hitters in the span of a week.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/columbus-buckeyes-aa] Morris pitched his on May 29 and Mountain threw one on June 5.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/columbus-buckeyes-aa] The 7 day span was the closest margin of 2 no-hitters being thrown by one team in history until Johnny Vander Meer threw 2 consecutive no-hitters for the Cincinnati Reds in a 4-day span on June 11 and 15, 1938.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/fred-mann-baseball] He was born in Sutton, Vermont and debuted with the Worcester Ruby Legs in 1882.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/fred-mann-baseball] In 1884, Mann's seven home runs was tied for fourth in the American Association.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/fred-mann-baseball] After his baseball career was over, Mann ran a hotel in Springfield, Massachusetts.
[src:fred-mann-baseball/fred-mann-baseball] He died of prostate cancer and is interred at Oak Grove Cemetery in Springfield.
